Got it—you want a rule that fires when a date field (e.g., lapseDate) equals today (Tokyo), and you already have eq. Easiest, low-impact change:

Minimal change: let eq understand “TODAY”

Add a tiny resolver that turns special tokens into concrete strings, then use it inside your existing eq / ne.

// --- helpers (put near your other helpers) ---
private static final ZoneId BUSINESS_TZ =
        ZoneId.of(Optional.ofNullable(System.getenv("Business_TZ")).orElse("Asia/Tokyo"));

private static String resolveSpecials(String v) {
    if (v == null) return null;
    String s = v.trim().toUpperCase();
    if (s.equals("TODAY")) {
        return LocalDate.now(BUSINESS_TZ).toString();       // yyyy-MM-dd
    }
    if (s.startsWith("TODAY")) {                            // e.g. TODAY+1, TODAY-2
        int delta = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(5));       // +N / -N
        return LocalDate.now(BUSINESS_TZ).plusDays(delta).toString();
    }
    return v;
}

// If your document stores an ISO datetime, normalize to yyyy-MM-dd for comparison:
private static String normalizeToYyyyMmDd(JsonNode n) {
    if (n == null || n.isNull() || !n.isTextual()) return null;
    String t = n.asText();
    return t.length() >= 10 ? t.substring(0, 10) : t;       // first 10 chars
}

Change equalsNow to use the normalizer:

private static boolean equalsNow(String path, ObjectNode doc, String expectedRaw) {
    String expected = resolveSpecials(expectedRaw);
    JsonNode v = doc.at(jsonPointer(path));
    String actual = normalizeToYyyyMmDd(v);
    if (actual == null || actual.isBlank()) return expected == null || expected.isBlank();
    return expected != null && expected.equals(actual);
}

And keep your existing switch:

case "eq":  return equalsNow(path, newDoc, r.value);
case "ne":  return !equalsNow(path, newDoc, r.value);

How to use it in config

Now your rule can say:

{ "op": "eq", "field": "/lapseDate", "value": "TODAY" }

(Optionally TODAY+1 or TODAY-1 if you ever need offsets.)

This keeps everything simple:
	•	No new op names required.
	•	Time-zone safe (Asia/Tokyo via Business_TZ env or default).
	•	Works whether the field is yyyy-MM-dd or full ISO datetime.